value.value: A neoplasm that arises from the nasopharynx and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential. Nasopharyngeal angiofibroma is a representative example.

Severe cellular and nuclear atypia in the cells of the endometrial glands. It often occurs during gestation, gestational trophoblastic disease, and treatment with gonadotropins or high doses of progestins.
A term referring to the presence of tumor emboli or tumor masses within the stroma of an organ.
A morphologic finding that indicates the presence of cells undergoing necrosis within a tumor.
Having to do with the presence of dividing (proliferating) cells. Cancerous tissue generally has more mitotic activity than normal tissues.

A neoplasm that arises from the hypopharynx and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential.
A morphologic finding indicating the presence of atypical mitoses in malignant cells.
A neoplasm that arises from the pharynx and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential.
A microscopic finding indicating the presence of acute, subacute or chronic inflammation in a tissue sample.
A morphologic finding indicating the presence of neutrophils and/or eosinophils in a tissue sample.

A neoplasm that arises from the esophageal wall and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential.
A morphologic finding indicating the presence of reactive lymphocytes, lymphoplasmacytic cells, and/or reactive plasma cells in a tissue sample.
An inflammatory infiltrate composed exclusively or predominantly of eosinophils.
A morphologic finding referring to an acute inflammatory infiltrate that is composed of polymorphonuclear cells.
A morphologic finding referring to the presence of a cellular infiltrate that is composed of non-neoplastic or neoplastic lymphocytes in a tissue sample.
A finding referring to the presence of a cellular infiltrate that is composed of lymphocytes and plasma cells in a tissue sample.

The term hemophagocytosis describes the pathologic finding of activated macrophages, engulfing erythrocytes, leukocytes, platelets, and their precursor cells. (from Medscape: Hemophagocytic Syndromes and Infection)
A neoplasm that arises from the stomach and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential.
